Meaning: ['A yellow face with smiling eyes and a broad, closed smile with its\xa0tongue sticking out of one corner, as if licking its lips in appetite or contentment. Widely used to convey that a food item is delicious. May also express that a person is attractive.']

Meaning: ['A yellow face screaming in fear, depicted by wide, white eyes, a long, open mouth, hands pressed on cheeks, and a pale\xa0blue forehead, as if it has lost its color. Meaning: ['A yellow face with a half-frown and white bandage wrapped around its head, often depicted partially over one eye. Meaning: ['A yellow face wearing a white surgical mask, as used by health workers in hospitals\xa0as well as the general public during a pandemic. Meaning: ['A kissing gesture, shown\xa0with a pink love heart floating in the air between two people.\xa0No gender is specified for the two people, and as such this may be used to represent the concept of a couple broadly, and/or as a means of showing two non-binary people.', 'Previously shown with the same appearance as\xa0üë©\u200d‚ù§Ô∏è\u200düíã\u200düë®\xa0Kiss: Woman, Man, but now displays\xa0two people with an ambiguous gender\xa0appearance.']

Meaning: ['A wheel with a rubber tire.', "May be used in reference to wheels, tires, or vehicles with wheels. May also be used in expressions with 'wheel' like third wheel or hell on wheels."]

Meaning: ['The international symbol of access, used to denote a\xa0facility which has been designed with accessibility or people in wheelchairs in mind. Unicode: ['\nWheelchair Symbol was approved as part of Unicode 4.1 in 2005 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.\n']

Meaning: ['A white cane, used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. The cane has a black or gray handle with a wrist loop, a white middle section, and a red end with a white cap. This cane differs from a support cane and is sometimes called a probing cane.']
Note: ['üë©\u200dü¶Ø Woman With Probing Cane and\xa0üë®\u200dü¶Ø Man With Probing Cane\xa0are ZWJ sequences that use White Cane.']

Meaning: ['A white flag, shown waving on a post. Traditionally used as a sign of surrender, the meaning of this flag as an emoji is less defined.']
Unicode: ['\nWhite Flag was approved as part of Unicode 7.0 in 2014 under the name ‚ÄúWaving White Flag‚Äù and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.\n']

Meaning: ['A stylized white flower. Generally depicted as a rosette-shaped cherry blossom in pink or red outline, often with a white fill.', "Apple, Microsoft, WhatsApp, and Facebook's designs feature Japanese characters roughly translating to\xa0very well done, used by teachers as a stamp for students who did exceptional work, often accompanied by a score in red.", 'Commonly used for Valentine‚Äôs Day, Mother‚Äôs Day, and other special occasions. Unicode: ['\nWhite Flower was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.\n']

Meaning: ['A Japanese wind chime. Depicted as a glass bell with a strip of paper suspended from its clapper, often decorated with cherry blossom-like flowers.', 'Occasionally used for content concerning various senses of wind and chime. Thanks to its appearance, often used to represent jellyfish.']
Unicode: ['\nWind Chime was approved as part of Unicode 6.0 in 2010 and added to Emoji 1.0 in 2015.\n']

Meaning: ['A face blowing the wind, as a personification of nature (e.g., Mother Nature, the North Wind) who creates the wind by blowing air from its mouth.
